##Britain's isolation diary | | March 18: The smell of the sea in the wind is the only solace for the wanderer's heart

Micro Signal Directorbai

Function description, all my feelings are illuminated by the moonlight.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Today is March 19th, the waning moon with a 20% phase.

It is March 19 with a 20 percent of Waning Crescent.

Five days to the new moon.

There are 5 days until New Moon.

| | Bai Qingyang

"I know it's silly to say,

Just how the simple days keep messing with my plan."

"Oceanside", Lainey Lou.

One

London is said to be closing the city, and anxiety is spreading among the remaining comrades.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Delta News source.

From The Telegraph. Though the news is full of cautious twists and turns, trying to make the case that a possible siege is still a done deal, the word itself is powerful enough. My friend and I had planned to "escape" on April 11. If London were closed, many questions would arise:

Is the closure of London a "two-way blockade" , in which both sides are sealed off, or a "one-way blockade" , in which only one side is sealed off but not in? Once London is sealed, when will it be unlocked? Will we ever get out of here? How can we ensure the goods of life in the blockaded London?

In fact, there are still many problems, but these three points should be the most concerned about the comrades left behind. I would also like to continue to ask, to satisfy some of the macro-world curiosity, such as: as the world's financial hub, the three financial city "Nuremberg" part, once the London blockade, what kind of ripple effect? Will trump, who has had four circuit breakers on his watch, go for it? However, this curiosity is only buried in the great anxiety and irritability of the deep, very occasionally will spit out a bubble.

Two

In any case, anxiety is real.

For a variety of reasons, in these extreme times, my friends are more or less dependent on me. Not To toot my own horn, but when everyone around me is more stressed than I am, I have to be the one to relieve everyone's stress. It's not about my ability to cope with stress, it's about having at least one member of the group to comfort. The so-called "occasional cure, always comfort" , used to describe the outbreak of mental stress, the same applies.

Yet I am no less anxious and irritable than others. I've never been one to sit still, and my emotions have always gone up and down with the events of my life. The day-to-day changes in policy, the racist rhetoric in Donald Trump, the collective collapse of the Internet supermarket, and today's rumors about the closure of the city all put pressure on me.

Three

I want to go home. I really do. During my four years of study in London, I never stopped thinking about Beijing. My enjoyment of life in London has never been at odds with my homesickness. I guess the reason is, my enjoyment of London is based on so many things: The company of Friends, the rare sunshine, the shopping malls of Oxford Street and Regent Street, the food from all over the world, the milk tea, the elegant swimming pool. The presence of this substance can be so subtle, so subtle, that you can't see it: You Leave Your House at eight in the morning, and there's a cool breeze around the corner that smells like a wet ocean. Yeah, it's been kind of weird for me. London is not by the sea. How can it be filled with the smell of the sea? But the smell is real. I know. The last time I smelled it, it was in Sanya, in Phuket.

Outbreak, forced to stay at home, all this essence of existence disappeared. London would be empty to me. To paraphrase the Gertrude Stein, London is "there is no there. " I just want to get out of here as Stein did from California.

The difference between me and Stein was that she wanted to escape from her empty home; I wanted to escape from my empty home. My attachment to Beijing does not need any substance. As long as I know in my heart, "I am in Beijing at the moment, " I feel a sense of maximum satisfaction and joy. Mr Yu Guangzhong describes his nostalgia as "sublimated Nostalgia" , nostalgia for a concept. I think I miss Beijing, the same kind of sublimation of the miss.

My anxiety stems from this urge to belong and the fear of living in an empty space for a long time. But I couldn't express this anxiety in any way. Around the friends have been panic, my calm itself will give them a strength. So I have to think, I have to think; I have to think about the worst case scenario, and then I have to think about how I can comfort them and give them the most moral support when different situations break out.

Four

One of the few pieces of good news is that, following the advice of a friend, I found on the great TESCO website that there was an alternative delivery date: tomorrow. I was overjoyed that this not only solved my problem of not having meat in the fridge, but also my concern that I had run out of sterile wipes. I sold four bags of wet wipes of different sizes in one sitting, a total panic purchase.

The photos he sent me from his childhood home in California, where he had taken refuge with his new wife in a mountain mansion, only added to my irritation. This irritability is mainly due to my jealousy. I envy the two of them for being able to support each other in extreme situations. Of course, I was mostly jealous of the luxury of their mansion. He sent me a picture of his wife sitting on a beach chair on the lawn not far away, reading a book. The California sun is Shining, and the swimming pool on the right reflects the shimmering warmth of spring. "I want to swim, " I said to him uncompromisingly. "I haven't been in the water for over a month. " He told me that you have to open more windows every day.

Five

Yes, it is. Opening a window for ventilation is the same as going out for me. Thanks to the French windows, I was able to open the whole window, stand in front of the guardrail, put my head out of the building, and feel the wind blowing through my body.

It's almost daylight savings time. It's springtime in London. The smell of the sea breeze filled in the wind, soothing my empty wanderer heart.
